Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The Red Wine dataset has 1,599 wines with 13 features (X - this one just an ID for the wine, fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, quality)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

My main feature is quality. Although it is a sensory data (based on the perception of the person who has evaluated), this is the main feature to set if a wine is good or not.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

It will be interesting to correlate all other variables to quality feature. This might indicate which chemical properties are significant to determine if a wine has high quality or not.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I have decided to not create new variables to this dataset.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I have just adjusted x-scale for Residual Sugar and Chlorides to check if they were normally distributed (which they are).

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The interesting fact is that, although given 11 chemical variables, it is difficult to find a very strong relation with quality. Among the variables plotted in Multivariate session, there are pH, fixed acidity, density, alcohol and sulphates.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

The most interesting plot is the relation with sulphates, alcohol and quality. If sulphates and alcohol have both low rates, lower is the quality.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot shows that higher alcohol %, higher the quality.

Plot Two

Description Two

Residual sugar influences on the wines density (along with alcohol). The objective was to try to find if there was some sort of relation with sugar, density and the wine quality. According to the plot, there is no such relation.

Plot Three

Description Three

It is interesting to see the relation of acidity with quality. The ideal wine should have a small quantity of citric acid to give some flavor to the wine. The wines with quality 6 or below have a high concentration of samples very close to 0. On the other hand, volatile acidity should be close to 0, because if there is concentration at high levels can give an unpleasant taste to the wine. The wines ranked 6 or below have high concentration of this acidity, while the better ranked wines (7 or 8) have lower concentration.

Reflection

I found very interesting to analyze this data set. When I first started it, I thought that the chemical features would have a very high influence on the quality of the wine. But not all the features appear to influence quality. Alcohol, sulfates, volatile acidity and citric acid are the ones to have some influence (with alcohol being the highest). But the difficulty is that quality is ranked accordingly to the person who experiments it. Its a personal taste that influences the final classification (even though that, as explained by the documentation regarding this data set, the quality is a median of the quality rate given by at least 3 experts). Some will like wines that taste more citric, others will prefer the ones with a sweeter taste. This, in my opinion, might be the reason that it is difficult to find some sort of pattern. For better analysis, it would be ideal to have the wine rate given per expert. That way, I believe we could discover better whether a wine is good or bad, given the evaluator.
